    <h1 style="margin:8px 0 4px">CDL-A vs CDL-B pay in 2026</h1>
    <p class="CardLabel">Real numbers from 1,200 driver paystubs across California.</p>

    <p>The classic answer is "Class A pays more, get the bigger license." That's still true on average — but the spread between Class A and B has compressed in 2026 as local last-mile demand pushed CDL-B rates up 18% YoY.</p>

    <h2 class="CardTitle">Median pay (California, 2026)</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>CDL-A regional</strong>: $72,000/yr (50th percentile), 90th = $94,000</li>
        <li><strong>CDL-B local</strong>: $61,000/yr, 90th = $79,000</li>
        <li><strong>Owner-operator (own truck)</strong>: $115,000 gross, $74,000 net after fuel/maintenance</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="CardTitle">When CDL-B beats CDL-A</h2>
    <p>Local routes that pay overtime past 8 hours, family preference for home every night, no DOT physical endorsements needed. Expect $55-65K to start; surge to $70K+ with experience and reefer endorsement.</p>

    <h2 class="CardTitle">When CDL-A is the obvious move</h2>
    <p>Long-haul, drayage, or doubles/triples. Sign-on bonuses ($3K-$10K). Tax-advantaged per-diem. Most career growth ends up Class A.</p>

